GSH studies in the DO

This analysis follows finding of a chromosome 14 QTL peak for GSH in the heart.

The phenotypes includes GSH, GSSG and derivatives of these two measurements (e.g. ratio of the two) along with rankZ-transformed variables to ensure a normal distribution. There are 21 variables and 347 observations. GSH has 139 missing values and GSSG has 139 missing values. Total number of observations is equal to 208.

Genome scan

# create a data frame with sex and generation
addcovarSexGenBatch <- model.matrix(~ sex + generation,
                               data = control$pheno)[,-1]

# genome scans of rankZ-transformed variables with sex as covariate
zScanSex <- scan1(genoprobs = probs,
               pheno = control$pheno[, c("zHeart_GSH",
                                         "zHeart_GSSG",
                                         "zHeart_TotalGSH",
                                         "zGSHGSSG_Ratio")],
               kinship = kinship_loco,
               addcovar = addcovarSexGenBatch[, "sex"])
# LOD thresholds with 10 permutations - increase to 1000 for publication
Sexperms <- scan1perm(genoprobs = probs,
                      pheno = control$pheno[, c("zHeart_GSH",
                                                "zHeart_GSSG",
                                                "zHeart_TotalGSH",
                                                "zGSHGSSG_Ratio")],
                      addcovar = addcovarSexGenBatch[, "sex"],
                      n_perm = 10)
summary(Sexperms)
## LOD thresholds (10 permutations)
##      zHeart_GSH zHeart_GSSG zHeart_TotalGSH zGSHGSSG_Ratio
## 0.05       7.17        6.94            7.31            7.1
Sexthresholds <- summary(Sexperms)

LOD peaks

# use the thresholds to find LOD peaks that exceed the thresholds
find_peaks(scan1_output = zScanSex,
           map = control$pmap,
           threshold = Sexthresholds,
           prob = 0.95,
           expand2markers = FALSE)
# note position, LOD and confidence interval for the chromosome 14 peak
# explore the chromosome 14 peak
plot_scan1(zScanSex, map = control$pmap,
           lodcolumn = "zHeart_GSH", main = "GSH",
           sub = "with sex as covariate")

These are insertions or deletions rather than SNPs.

region of the 3 structural variants See the track for smaller variants to locate those indicated in the table above. Genome coordinates shouldn’t be too far off.

SV_14_54091931_54091933 maps as insertion rs387900728, which is an intron variant of gene model Gm30275

SV_14_54091931_54091933 also maps to intron variant rs585988314, which also affects gene model Gm30275

SV_14_54279758_54279776 overlaps SNP rs248305752, which is a 3 prime UTR variant however, it’s not a single nucleotide but rather an insertion of 18 nucleotides

deletion SV_14_54342903_54343261 can be found in the SV - smaller variants track and has been found in strains AJ, CAST/EiJ and PWK/PhJ. This deletion overlaps CTCF binding site ENSMUSR00000347935 Downstream genes whose transcription might be affected include Oxa1l, Mrpl52, Lrp10 and Rem2.
